      <title>Gregory Bald</title>
   </titleInfo>
   <abstract>From Parsons Bald, near the southwestern end of the Great Smoky Mountains National Park, one can see the grassy dome of Gergory Bald (in the left background) and Rye Patch, on Long Hungry Ridge (the grassy open space in the right background). These balds are quite common on high peaks and ridges in the southwestern half of the park. Many people have assumes that they are "above timberline". This is not the case, however, as the size of the trees at the edge of the bald indicates. The phenomenon is explained as being the result of grazing over long periods -- first by deer, and later by domestic animals. These grassy balds were highly prized grazing lands for many years before the area became a national park.</abstract>
